values:
The sense of let-down usually hits me straight after Christmas Dinner. The presents have all been unwrapped, the food has been eaten, and everyone sits down and falls asleep. As a child, this used to bother me greatly, as all I wanted to do was play. I can see that this bothers my sister's children equally as much, now that I have grown up, and we have a 1 year old and a 4 year old in the family. Bless. Me, I'd rather go somewhere in the evening, for a drink or something, or see my boyfriend. Just so that the day doesn't fizzle out quite so quickly. 

I don't think the commercial build up towards Christmas is the cause for such disappointment. I think that's just the way of life - when you grow a bit older, it's obviously going to lose it's magic. And let's face it; without children there would be no need for such a magical Christmas image to be portrayed. For adults, I reckon that the best bit about Christmas is the look of wonder on their child's, or other youngest members of their family's faces as they realise in the morning, that presents have arrived under the tree. 

Also, Boxing day is SUCH a let down day. What are you supposed to do? I'll be waiting till the boyfriend comes round. Family is lovely and all that, but everyone together - can get a bit tiresome. Especially in the evenings when all anyone does is go to bed, bar my Dad who sits around and watches crappy T.V. 

However, all this aside, Christmas '10 has been lovely. I'm full on turkey and chocolate, smiling, and having a lovely evening. I hope you all are too. :)

Hi guys!

Thought I would give y'all a quick update before embarking on some Chemistry (ack!) revision.

Yesterday was a funny funny day. You know where nothing happens but everything happens. LOL
I had my Maths calculator paper yesteday morning. Which was kinda bad, well i sorta bluffed my way through the paper, and kept my fingers crossed. 
Then, as I was walking home, at about 11-30, I was like, SHIT, i'd forgotten my key - and of ocurse, my Mum wasn't home. So I had to run down the street to get the key (thankfully they were in) then go home, open the door, then return the key.  All this time, my neighbour was watching me out her living room window as if I'd lost my marbles (can't blame her really).

Then I phoned my Mum, who was with her other daugter and my nephew. They were eating cake. So i joined them - rather than revising for Geography! LOL. The cake was good (it was my sisters Birthday cake, yum)
Then, I, tried, without much success to get my internet to work, walked to school and did my Geography exam. WHich gave me cramps in my hand - i wrote far too much. (hopefully that means that it was easy) 
I came home at about 3-00. (i could get in this time as i had brought our 'original' house keys, which was kinda funny,cos i had all the room keys and the garage and shed key on me in the exam).

Then I did nothing. And more nothing. 

Only 4 more exams to go. Really!

Just felt like sharing that with yooh - Got -

Wed - Chemistry
Fri - Physics
Wed - R.E
Fri - Graphics

Woop!

Also, been screencapping DH, nearly finished S1. Also still capping BSG from god knows how long ago, so i will upload those soon enough! LOL

Also, anyone know why Weir isn't coming back to SGA, and Carter is taking her place (i need to rewatch the last episode as I can't even remember!

How is everyone this cloudy and dreary morning then?
